1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 {This waiting move is almost always
useful. The rule here is that Black will take on d2 and play d6-e5 against
everything besides 5.g3.} (4... Bxd2+ 5. Nbxd2 (5. Qxd2 $1)) (4... a5 5. a3
Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 d6 7. e4 Qe7 8. e5 (8. g3 e5)) 5. g3 (5. a3 {this is already an
innacuracy} Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 {This is already a mistake. The knight belongs to
"c3"} (6. Qxd2 {is the right way to capture}) 6... d6 $1 {Black should
immediately play d6-e5} 7. e4 ({If} 7. e3 e5 $1 (7... O-O {it is also playable,
but we lose time.}) (7... Nbd7 $2 {This is a mistake, whenever we can play e5,
only with the help of the queen and the "d6" pawn, Black should delay the
development of the knight because we are not sure where the knight belongs.})
8. Be2 e4 9. Ng5 (9. Nh4 g5) 9... h6 10. Nh3 Bxh3 11. gxh3 O-O) 7... e5 ({
this is also possible, but less accurate} 7... O-O 8. e5 dxe5 9. dxe5 Nfd7 10.
Bd3 Nc6 {This type of position are probably slightly better for White, but
Black has some counterplay. The e5 pawn is a target and the position of the
"c" pawn on c4, gives Black some counterplay, too.}) 8. d5 (8. Bd3 O-O (8...
exd4 $2 9. Nxd4 Nxe4 $2 {Remember, in 99% of the cases, this is wrong for
Black and not in the spirit of the position.} 10. Nxe4 f5) 9. O-O a5 10. Re1 ({
If} 10. d5 a4 11. Bc2 Bd7 $15) 10... a4 $2 {we are playing a4 only after
White's pawn is on "a3," and we have access to "c5" square.} 11. Bc2 exd4 12.
Nxd4 Bd7 13. f4 {with an advantage for White.}) 8... a5 $1 {We are following
the dark-squared strategy again. We need to delay castling and play a useful
move.} 9. b3 (9. Be2 $2 {this is a mistake because it allows Black to fix the
queenside favourably.} a4 $1 {Remember this idea. It works only if White's
pawn is already on a3.} 10. O-O {The position is closed, so we are not in a
hurry to castle.} Nbd7 11. Qc2 Nc5 $15 {Black is already better because he
fixes the queenside and White has no plan. There are two possible plans: 1.
Pawn break f7-f5 2. Pawn break c7-c6 I will tell you one rule which can help
you to choose the right plan in this kind of position. It depends on the
placement of White's light-squared bishop. If the bishop is somewhere on the
"f1-a6" diagonal (usually "d3" or "e2") then he influences the queenside. In
this case, we should opt for kingside play by means of f7-f5. If the bishop is
placed on "g2", we should opt for the "c7-c6" break. This rule is not 100%
valid, but could help you in most of the cases.} 12. Rfe1 O-O 13. Rac1 Ng4 {
another possibility that works perfectly fine. The knight is freeing the "f"
pawn to move. If White kicks the knight, then it is going to "h6"} (13... Nh5 {
this is an interesting move, but quite often, Black's queen is on "d1" and
this is not working due to the Nxe5 tactic.}) (13... Bd7) 14. h3 Nh6 15. Bf1 f5
16. Qc3 f4 $1 {After this move, Black's attack is powerful. I am providing you
with an illustrative line of how the game can continue} 17. Ra1 (17. b4 $2 axb3
18. Nxb3 Rxa3 $19) 17... g5 18. b4 axb3 19. Nxb3 Na4 20. Qc2 b6 21. Nfd2 g4 22.
hxg4 Nxg4 $19 {White is totally lost}) 9... O-O 10. Be2 Na6 (10... Nbd7) 11.
O-O Nc5 12. Qc2 Nh5 $1 {[%cal Rh5f4,Rf7f5]} (12... Bd7 $6 13. b4 axb4 14. axb4
Na6 15. Qc3 $14) 13. b4 Nf4 $1 $15) 5... Bxd2+ (5... Nc6 {This is the most
popular move and the one we will study in the theoretical section.}) (5... d5 {
If Black plays d7-d5 then White can recapture with the knight on d2} 6. a3
Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 $1) 6. Nbxd2 $6 {this is a small positional mistake} (6. Qxd2 $1
Nc6) 6... O-O (6... d6 {is more accurate}) 7. Bg2 d6 8. O-O e5 (8... Nbd7 $6)
9. d5 (9. dxe5 dxe5 10. e4 (10. Qc2 Nc6) 10... Bg4 (10... c5 $5) 11. Re1 Nc6
12. h3 Bxf3 $15) 9... a5 $1 {is a typical idea in such structure.} (9... e4 $1
{this advance is very good if it is supported by the queen.} 10. Ne1 e3 $15) (
9... Qd8 10. Rb1 Re8 11. Ra1 e4 12. Ng5 e3 13. fxe3 Rxe3) 10. e4 (10. a3 $6 a4
$1 11. e4 Nbd7 $1 (11... Na6 12. Qxa4) 12. Qc2 Nc5 13. Rfe1 c6 $1 {remember
with the bishop on "g2" we should go for "c6" break.} ({let's check another
possibility} 13... Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 $6 {this move is pointless} (14... Bxf3 $1 {
The computer likes this idea for Black, but my experience proves that Black
lacks winning chances in such a position. After many moves, when we open the
position, we will miss our light-squared bishop.}) (14... Bd7 $1 {I prefer to
keep the bishop, but then why to play 13...Bg4 in the first place.}) 15. Nh4
$14) 14. h3 (14. dxc6 $2 {This is a big positional mistake. Always when White
takes on "c6" we get access to the "e6" square.} bxc6 15. h3 Ne6 16. Qc3 c5 $15
) 14... cxd5 15. cxd5 (15. exd5 {I can't see the point of this move.} Bd7 {
[%cal Rf7f5]}) 15... b5 {taking control of the "c4" square.} 16. Rac1 Bd7 (
16... Qa7 $2 {we should be careful} 17. Nxe5 $1) 17. Qb1 Rfc8 (17... Rac8 $2 {
It is better to activate the "f8" rook}) (17... Rfb8 {is also good.}) 18. Kh2
Qd8 $1 (18... Be8 {[%cal Re7a7] is also possible, but our bishop is perfectly
placed on "d7". If we put it on "e8" he is not influencing the kingside.}) 19.
Nf1 Qb6 20. N3d2 Rc7 {Black is much better here.} (20... b4 21. Nc4 Qa6 22.
axb4 Nb3)) 10... Na6 {The knight belongs to "a6" in this structure because now
Black is not forced to play Nc5 on the next move, but can continue with Bd7.} (
10... a4 $6 {is wrong because the a-pawn is still on b2.} 11. b4 $1 axb3 12.
axb3 Na6 13. b4 $14) 11. Re1 (11. a3 $2 Nc5 $1 {now this move is excellent
because it is coming with tempo.} 12. Qc2 {White has no time for b4 because he
needs to defend the pawn on "e4"} a4 $1 {The point of Black's previous move.
Now the queenside is fixed in our favour and Black is better.} 13. Rfe1 (13.
Ne1 {White can try to exchange the "c5" knight} Bd7 (13... c6 14. Nd3 Nxd3 15.
Qxd3 Nd7 (15... cxd5 {is also possible} 16. cxd5 b5 {the pawn is untouchable
due to Ba6}) 16. f4 {let's discuss the situation when White is playing f4.} Nc5
17. Qc2 cxd5 18. cxd5 Bd7 19. f5 {we shouldn't be scared of this advance.
Usually, in Bogo-Indian, it is not dangerous for Black.} (19. Nc4 Bb5) 19... f6
$1 {we should stop f5-f6.} 20. g4 {This attack is not dangerous. White has no
threats. He misses his dark-squared bishop. On the other hand, Black has
serious counterplay on the queenside.} Rfc8 21. Qd1 Bb5)) 13... c6 {this is
the correct move again.} 14. Rac1 cxd5 15. cxd5 b5 16. Qb1 Bd7 (16... Qa7) 17.
h3 Rfc8 $17 (17... Rfb8 $17) (17... g6 $17) 18. Kh2 (18. Red1) 18... Qd8) 11...
c6 $1 (11... Nc5 $6 {we should play Nc5 randomly, we should play in with a
very concrete idea in our mind.} 12. b3 $1 (12. Qc2 c6 13. b3 cxd5 14. cxd5 Bd7
15. a3 Rfc8 16. Qb1 b5) 12... c6 13. a3 cxd5 14. cxd5 Bd7 15. b4 {now the
knight is kicked, and White is better.} axb4 16. axb4 Na4) (11... Bg4 {it is
possible, but I always prefer c6} 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 c6 14. Rc1 cxd5 15. cxd5
Nc5 16. Qe2) 12. h3 (12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Qc2 Nc5 (13... c5 14. Rad1 Nb4 15. Qb1
Nc6 $15) 14. Rad1 Ne6 15. h3 c5) 12... cxd5 13. cxd5 b5 14. Rc1 (14. b3 Bd7 (
14... Nc5 {is interesting too.})) 14... Bd7 (14... Qa7 {is possible, but we
need to calculate the following line.} 15. Rc6 Bd7 16. Rxd6 Qc7 17. Rxf6 {
with a compensation for the exchange.}) 15. b3 (15. Kh2 Rfc8 16. b3 Qd8 17. Qe2
Qb6) 15... Nc5 16. Qc2 Rfc8 17. Qb1 Qd8 $1 {an important maneuvre to remember}
(17... b4 $6 18. Nc4 $1) 18. a3 h6 19. b4 axb4 20. axb4 Na4 21. Nb3 Qb6 $17 *

