{In the following model games, Black applies the "Dark Square Strategy". Since
all the important ideas have been explained in the previous example, the model
games will include only light comments.} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2
Qe7 5. a3 (5. e3 Bxd2+ $1 6. Qxd2 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Be2 e5 9. dxe5 $5 ({After} 
9. O-O e4 {is a playable move} 10. Ne1 (10. Ng5 $6 h6 $15) (10. Nh4 $2 g5 $19)
10... c6 $1 11. Nc2 (11. d5 {is well met by} c5 12. Rb1 Bf5) 11... Bf5 12. Rfd1
Nbd7 13. Rac1 (13. d5 c5 14. Rab1 h5 $1 {[%cal Rd7e5,Rg7g6,Rg8g7]}) 13... Rfd8
14. d5 c5 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gg7g6,Gg8g7,Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gh4h3]}) (9. d5 a5 10. e4
Na6 11. O-O Ng4 (11... Nc5 12. Qc2 Nh5 $1 13. g3 (13. Rfe1 Nf4 14. Bf1 f5)
13... f5 $36 14. Nh4 Qg5 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 16. exf5 Rxf5 $40) 12. h3 Nh6 13. Bd3 f5
$132 (13... Nc5 14. Bc2 f5 $132)) 9... dxe5 10. O-O (10. Nd5 Qd6) 10... c6 $1 {
Generally, when White has a knight on c3, we play c6! (except if White has a
Nc3 and a pawn on d5 when I go a7-a5 followed by ...Na6).} 11. Rad1 Re8 ({
Another easy solution would be} 11... Bg4 $1 {Usually, in this structure,
giving the light-squared bishop for a knight is a good idea. Then Black
dominates on the dark squares. Here is a possible line.} 12. b3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3
Na6 14. Qd6 Qxd6 15. Rxd6 Rfd8 16. Rfd1 Rxd6 17. Rxd6 Kf8 18. Kf1 Ke7 19. Rd2
Nc5 20. Ke1 (20. b4 Ne6) 20... a5 $15) 12. Qd6 $6 Qxd6 13. Rxd6 Na6 $1 ({
Once again, it was possible to play the thematic} 13... Bg4 $1 14. h3 Bxf3 15.
Bxf3 a5 16. Rfd1 Na6 17. Kf1 Nc5 $132) 14. Rfd1 Bg4 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Kf8 (
