1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 $6 O-O 7. e3 $5
({The alternative is} 7. g3 {Take a look at the following typical sequence -}
d6 8. Bg2 e5 9. e4 (9. d5 a5 $5 (9... e4 $1 10. Nd4 e3 $17) 10. e4 a4 11. O-O
Nbd7 $15 (11... Na6 12. Qxa4) 12. Re1 Nc5 13. Qc2 c6 $1 14. Rac1 cxd5 15. cxd5
b5 16. h3 Bd7 (16... Qa7 $2 17. Nxe5) 17. Qb1 Rfb8 $1 18. Re3 b4 19. axb4 Rxb4
$17) 9... a5 10. O-O a4 11. Re1 Nc6 (11... Bg4) 12. d5 ({Another typical
position arises after} 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Rc1 Bg4 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Nxf3 Rfd8 (
15... Nd7 16. Qe2 Nc5 17. Red1 Nb3 {[%csl Gd4]}) 16. Qc2 Nd4 17. Nxd4 Rxd4 $17)
12... Nb8 13. Qc2 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc8d7,Gc7c6]}) (7. e4 d6 8. Bd3 (8. e5 $6
dxe5 9. dxe5 Nfd7 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. Qe2 a5 12. O-O Nc5 13. Bc2 b6 14. Rad1 Bb7
$132) 8... e5 9. d5 ({It's important to know that} 9. O-O $5 {is very well met
by} a5 $5 {We try to avoid the sequence 1...Nc6 2.d5-Nb8 and Na6. Black wants
to force White to play d4-d5 with a knight still on b8. In this way, we can
play ...Na6 immediately without losing 2 tempi (Nc6-Nb8-Na6). IF there is no
way to achieve that, then at some moment, we do play Nc6-d5-Nb8.} 10. d5 (10.
Re1 Bg4 $1 11. Qc2 (11. d5 Na6 12. h3 Bd7 13. b3 Nh5 $36) 11... a4 $5 (11...
Nfd7 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7f6]} 12. b3 Qf6 13. d5 Na6 $132) (11... Bxf3 $5 12.
Nxf3 Nbd7 13. b3 exd4 14. Nxd4 Qe5 15. Nf3 Qf4 $132) 12. d5 Nbd7 $132) 10...
Na6 (10... a4)) 9... a5 $1 10. b3 $5 (10. a4 $4) (10. b4 $5 axb4 (10... Nh5 $5
11. g3 Na6 12. Rb1 Bh3 $15 13. Bf1 Bg4) 11. axb4 Rxa1 12. Qxa1 Na6 13. Qb2 Nh5
$1 (13... c5 $5 14. b5 (14. dxc6 bxc6 15. O-O Bg4 16. b5 Nc5 17. Bc2 Rb8) 14...
Nb4 {Black has a good position.The only problem is that these lines with
b5-Nb4 tend to be very drawish.} 15. Bb1 Bg4 (15... Nh5) 16. O-O Ra8 17. h3
Bxf3 18. Nxf3 b6 19. Re1 Qa7 20. Qc3 Qa1 $15 (20... Qa3 21. Qxa3 Rxa3 $15)) 14.
g3 Bh3 15. Bf1 Qd7 $132) (10. h3 $6 a4 11. O-O (11. Bc2 Bd7 12. O-O Qe8 $3 13.
Re1 (13. Nb1 Na6 14. Nc3 Nc5 $15) 13... Na6 14. Qe2 Nc5 15. Rac1 c6 16. Qe3
cxd5 17. cxd5 b5) 11... Nbd7 $15) 10... Na6 11. O-O Nh5 $1 (11... c6 $5 {
SOS !!! USUALLY WE DONT PLAY c6 WHEN WHITE'S BISHOP IS ON e2 or d3, ..BUT EVEN
THEN..c6 is always a good option!} 12. Re1 cxd5 (12... Bd7 13. Bf1 cxd5 14.
cxd5 b5 15. h3 Rfc8 16. g3 Qd8 $1 $132) 13. cxd5 Nc5 14. Bc2 b5 $132) (11...
Nc5 12. Bc2) (11... Ng4 $132) 12. g3 (12. Re1 Nf4 13. Bf1 f5 $132) 12... Nf6 $5
(12... f5 $2 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Bxf5 Rxf5 15. Nh4 Rg5 16. Ne4 $18) 13. Re1 c6
14. Qc2 Bd7 15. Qb2 Rfc8 $132 16. b4 axb4 17. axb4 c5 18. b5 Nb4) 7... d6 8.
Be2 (8. Qc2 e5 9. Be2 Re8 $5 (9... e4 10. Ng5 Re8) (9... Nbd7 10. d5) 10. O-O (
10. d5 a5 11. b3 Na6) 10... e4 $1 11. Ne1 c5 $1 {Now that there is no knight
on c3, ...c7-c5! is very interesting!} 12. d5 Bf5 13. b4 Nbd7 $15) 8... e5 9.
O-O e4 (9... a5 $6) 10. Ne1 c5 $1 11. Nc2 Bf5 (11... Nc6 12. b4 b6) 12. b4 Nbd7
$132 0-1

