Bb7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O a5 9. d5 c6 10. dxe6 dxe6) 6. g3 (6. e4 Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Nxe4
) 6... d6 {intending e5} 7. Qc2 (7. a3 {we can just take and proceed with the
Capablanca's idea} Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Ne4 9. Qc2 Nxc3 10. Qxc3 Re8 11. Bg2 e5 12. d5
a5 13. b3 f5 (13... Bg4 14. O-O Nd7)) 7... e5 8. Bg2 (8. dxe5 dxe5) 8... Re8 (
8... e4 9. Nxe4) 9. O-O (9. dxe5 {This is another important moment.} dxe5 10.
O-O Bxc3 $2 {now, we can't apply the light-squared strategy because there is
no pawn on d4 to restrict the bishop.} (10... c6 11. a3 Bd6) 11. Bxc3 e4 12.
Nd4) 9... Bxc3 {This is a critical position to understand. Black applies a
light-squared strategy. In order to use the light-square strategy, we need to
exchange the bishop first} ({this move is wrong} 9... e4 $2 10. Nxe4 Qxe4 11.
Qxe4 Rxe4 12. Bxb4 Rxe2 13. Bc3 {and White is better.}) 10. Bxc3 e4 {The point
of Black's previous move. The idea is that now Black has one more minor piece
which operates on the light squares - both knights and the bishop.} 11. Ne1 d5
(11... c6 12. d5 cxd5 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. cxd5 Bf5) (11... Bf5 12. d5 Nbd7) 12.
b3 (12. cxd5 Nxd5 {the knight is very strong on d5.} 13. e3 Bf5 {we proceed by
putting more pieces on the light squares.} 14. Bd2 Nd7 15. Rc1 N7f6 16. a3 Qd7
{As you can see, Black is attacking on the light squares.} 17. b4 Bh3 18. a4 h5
{another important idea to remember} 19. Qb3 Bxg2 20. Nxg2 Nh7 {[%csl Rd7]
[%cal Rh7g5]}) (12. Bd2 h6 {not allowing Bg5} (12... Nc6 {this is also
possible, to provoke e3} 13. e3 Be6 14. cxd5 Bxd5 {Black will continue with
the manoeuvring on the light-squares, by means of Nd8-e6, etc..})) 12... Bf5 {
we plan to develop the initiative on the light squares.} 13. e3 Nbd7 (13... c6
14. cxd5) 14. Qd2 c6 {It is always useful to support the "d5" pawn.} ({if} 
14... Nf8 {White can exchange his bishop for our knight.} 15. Bb4 Qe6 16. Bxf8
Rxf8 {Black is still fine, but we can't talk about the light-square strategy
anymore because both sides have an equal number of pieces that operate on the
light squares.}) 15. Nc2 Qe6 {avoiding the nasty Bb4} (15... Nf8 $6 16. Bb4 Qd7
17. Bxf8 $11) 16. Rfb1 ({if} 16. f4 {just} exf3 {and White has too many
weaknesses}) 16... h5 17. a4 Nf8 18. Rb2 {very important moment. In such a
position, even very strong players make mistakes by putting the knight on the
wrong spot.} N8h7 {the weak squares are "h3" and "f3" so our knight is heading
to "g5"} (18... Ng6 $2 {This is wrong. The knight is dominated by the "g3"
pawn.} 19. b4 h4 20. Ne1 ({of course nobody will do us a favour to play this
move} 20. gxh4) 20... hxg3 21. hxg3 {Black will proceed with the attack, but
his knight on "g6" doesn't help.}) 19. h4 g5 {the centre is closed so we can
proceed with the flank attack.} 20. hxg5 Nxg5 21. Ne1 Bh3 {The triumph of the
light-squared strategy. As you see, White has one piece which is totally out
of play and didn't help at all - the dark-squared bishop. White will be
thrilled to exchange it for one of Black's knights, but this is impossible.} *

