{[%evp 0,66,28,23,23,29,22,10,34,43,56,45,51,45,41,34,55,55,38,31,9,15,17,6,-4,
-9,-10,-31,-33,-45,-45,-60,-37,-65,-55,-96,-44,-117,-70,-149,-129,-165,-139,
-151,-138,-138,-158,-161,-164,-153,-148,-231,-235,-282,-251,-266,-263,-347,
-344,-364,-452,-467,-475,-495,-523,-516,-526,-519,-548] Capablanca Method} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 (4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 Bb7 7. e3
O-O 8. Bd3 Ne4 9. Bxe4 Bxe4 10. Bc3 d6 11. O-O Nd7 12. Nd2 Bg6 13. e4 e5 14. d5
f5) 4... Qe7 5. Nc3 b6 6. e3 (6. a3 {Black will take on c3 anyway, so I think
a3 is just a waste of time.} Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 (8. Bb4 c5 {is good for
Black too.}) 8... Bb7 {let's see how the game can go} 9. e3 d6 10. Bd3 Nxc3 11.
Qxc3 O-O 12. O-O Nd7 13. Be2 c5 {this is an interesting plan. Black intends to
open the "c" file} 14. dxc5 dxc5 {all other moves are possible too} 15. Rad1
Rad8 16. Rd2 Nf6 17. Rfd1 Rxd2 18. Rxd2 h6 19. Rd1 Bxf3 $1 {I want to show you
an interesting positional idea, which has nothing to do with Bogo-Indian} 20.
Bxf3 Rd8 21. Rxd8+ Qxd8 22. b4 Qc8 23. h3 Qb8 24. bxc5 bxc5 25. g3 Qc7 {
This is Black's dream position. Black can't lose because White can't attack
his pawns twice. Soon Black will start to improve his pieces.} 26. Qa5 Kh8 27.
Qa6 Kg8 28. Bc6) 6... Bxc3 $5 {Capablanca's idea is to follow with the
immediate Ne4 exchanging the dark-squared bishop.} (6... Bb7 {is a normal move
too, but White can answer it with} 7. Bd3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Ne4 {now White should
exchange one of his bishops.} 9. Bxe4 $1 {strangely enough, White exchanges
his light-squared bishop and achieves a good game after.} Bxe4 10. d5 $14) 7.
Bxc3 Ne4 8. Rc1 Bb7 9. Bd3 O-O (9... Nxc3 {was better} 10. Rxc3 O-O 11. O-O d6
12. e4 e5 (12... Nd7 13. Re1 e5 14. d5 a5) 13. d5 (13. dxe5 {of course this is
not dangerous.} dxe5 14. Re1 (14. c5 {is possible, but Black is just fine
after:} Nc6) 14... c5 {Black is much better strategically.}) 13... a5 $1 14.
Nd2 Na6 15. f4 {the difference from the variations with g3 was that White
couldn't recapture with a pawn here.} exf4 16. Rxf4 Nc5 17. Bc2 Nd7 18. Rf2 Ne5
19. Nf3 Bc8 {with a great position for Black. White's bishop is bad and Black
has full control of the dark squares.}) 10. O-O d6 (10... f5 11. a3 d6 12. b4
Nd7 13. Bb2 Rf6 14. Ra1 Rh6 15. Qe2 Kh8 16. a4 a5 17. bxa5 Rxa5 18. Ba3 Nc3 19.
Qc2) 11. Nd2 (11. Be1 {is interesting too}) (11. Bxe4 Bxe4 12. Nd2 Bg6 $3 {
The bishop is better placed on "g6"} (12... Bb7 13. e4 e5 14. d5 Nd7 15. b4 $14
) 13. e4 ({If} 13. b4 Nd7 14. a4 f5 $13 {[%cal Rf5f4,Re6e5,Rd7f6]}) 13... e5
14. d5 Nd7) (11. a3 f5 12. Bxe4 fxe4 13. Nd2 Nd7 14. f4 exf3 15. Nxf3 Nf6 $15)
11... Nxc3 (11... f5 12. f3 Nxc3 13. Rxc3 c5 14. dxc5 dxc5) 12. Rxc3 c5 (12...
Nd7 {is another possible plan} 13. e4 e5 14. d5 $11 {[%cal Rd7c5,Rb7c8,Rf7f5,
Ra7a5]}) 13. dxc5 dxc5 14. Qh5 (14. Be4 {is the right way for White to
continue, but Marshall was ambitious} Nc6 15. Qf3 Rad8 (15... Rac8)) 14... h6
15. f4 Nd7 16. e4 e5 $1 $11 17. Nf3 (17. f5 Nf6 18. Qh4 Rad8 $15) 17... Rae8 {
Capablanca won the game convincigly} 18. Nh4 (18. Rf2) 18... exf4 19. Rxf4 Qg5
20. Qf3 Ne5 21. Qf2 Nxd3 22. Rxd3 Rxe4 23. Rxe4 Bxe4 24. Re3 f5 25. h3 Rd8 26.
a3 Rd1+ 27. Kh2 Qf6 28. Qf4 g5 29. Rg3 Kf8 30. Qb8+ Rd8 31. Qe5 Qxe5 32. Ng6+
Kf7 33. Nxe5+ Kf6 0-1

