{Capablanca Method - Model Game} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5.
Nc3 Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Ne4 7. Qc2 Nxc3 {this is so-called Capablanca's equalizing
method} 8. Qxc3 d6 9. g3 (9. e4 O-O 10. Be2 Nd7 11. O-O e5 12. d5 a5 (12... Nc5
$5 13. Nd2 a5 14. b3 (14. a3 a4) 14... f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. a3 Qg5 17. b4 Ne4
18. Nxe4 Bxe4 {and Black has a fine game})) (9. d5 e5 10. c5 {we already know
that we should ignore this c5 idea.} O-O 11. e4 Nd7 12. cxd6 cxd6 13. Be2 Nc5
14. Nd2 a5 15. O-O f5 $15) 9... O-O 10. Bg2 Re8 11. O-O e5 12. dxe5 {This
exchange is not dangerous for Black.} (12. e4 $6 Bg4 $3 {remember this idea.
Black's threat is Bxf3 followed by Nc6} (12... Nc6 13. d5) 13. d5 {is almost
force} (13. Rad1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nc6 15. d5 Nd4 $17) 13... a5 14. h3 Bxf3 $3 {
we always take} (14... Bd7 15. a3 a4) (14... Bh5 {the bishop on h5 could be
passive after} 15. Nh4 Nd7 16. Nf5) 15. Bxf3 Nd7 16. Bg2 g6 (16... Nc5 17. Rae1
c6 18. f4 f6 19. f5 cxd5 20. cxd5 b5) 17. Rae1 b6 18. f4 exf4 19. gxf4 f6 {
and Black is better}) 12... dxe5 13. Nd2 Nd7 14. b4 Nf6 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4
c6 ({if} 16... g6 {then} 17. b5 {could be unplesant}) (16... f5 {is another
possibility} 17. Bd5+ Kh8 18. b5 Qc5) 17. Rfd1 (17. Qc2 g6 18. c5 Bh3 19. Rfd1
Rad8) 17... Bg4 18. Rd2 {Too many pieces were exchanged and the position is
just equal. Lately Black even manage to win the game.} Rad8 19. Rad1 Bxe2 20.
Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Rxd8+ Qxd8 22. Kg2 Qd1 23. Kh3 Bf1+ 24. Kh4 Qd8+ 25. Kg4 h5+ 26.
Kf3 (26. Kxh5 Be2+ (26... g6+ 27. Kh6 Qf8+ 28. Kg5 f6+ {with mate to follow})
27. Bf3) 26... Qd1+ 27. Ke3 Qe2# 0-1

