{[%evp 0,84,22,22,22,6,-2,2,31,4,24,34,30,-3,6,13,9,0,2,2,17,16,22,7,12,10,82,
34,42,42,36,-30,-24,-9,-9,-18,-18,-24,-24,-25,-25,-23,-28,-28,-31,-27,-5,-5,0,
0,22,29,14,28,18,18,28,21,59,34,42,35,42,26,23,40,52,69,130,94,111,89,108,108,
115,-9,60,101,95,41,94,101,73,58,75,105,83]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4.
Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 ({This move is of course possible. We will take a
closer look in the theoretical part, but here I want to show you a simple and
well known scheme of play.} 6. Bxd2 Bb7 7. e3 Ne4 $1 {Remember Capablanca's
method} 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O f5 ({We can enter a well know structure, by playing} 
9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 d6 11. Qc2 Nd7 12. e4 e5 13. d5 a5 {[%cal Rb7c8,Rd7c5,Rf7f5]
}) 10. b4 d6 11. Qc2 Rf6 12. Bc3 Rg6 13. d5 {we will see this type of position
many times in the examples} (13. c5 {is always met with} Bd5) 13... Nd7 14.
Rad1 {in this position Black has two equally good options: Black must take
control over the d4 square. 1.playing e6-e5 following by c7-c6 2. playing
c7-c5 - Smyslov Plan} ({If} 14. dxe6 Rxe6 (14... Nf8 {also can be considered})
15. Nd4 Rg6 {[%cal Rg6g2]}) 14... c5 (14... e5 15. Bb2 (15. b5 Qe7) 15... c6
16. dxc6 Bxc6 {Black has an excellent play here, his chances to create an
attack on the kingside are pretty high. On the other side, White's play on the
queenside is too slow} 17. a4 {I will show you an illustrative line, how the
game can continue?} Qe7 18. a5 Rf8 19. axb6 axb6 20. Rfe1 Ng5 21. Nxg5 Bxg2 (
21... Qxg5 22. g3 h5)) 15. dxc6 Bxc6 16. Ne1 {The rule is that when the knight
leaves "f3" square, Black should develop the queen to h4 or g5.} Qh4 17. f3 Rh6
{Typical attacking approach, we sacrifice the knight on e4} 18. fxe4 Qxh2+ 19.
Kf2 fxe4 $1 {Black is absolutely winning - Rf8 is coming} 20. Bg4 Qh4+ {
Winning the piece back with a winning position}) 6... Bb7 7. e3 d6 8. Be2 O-O
9. O-O Nbd7 10. b4 Ne4 {I should mention that the modern engines don't like
this plan. For me, this is irrelevant because we are playing against humans,
but not computers. Black's play is logical, and White can easily go wrong.} ({
Black can choose another plan, to develop the pieces with} 10... a5 11. Bb2 Qe7
{[%cal Rf8d8,Rc7c5] It is playable but less ambitious}) 11. Qc2 f5 12. Bb2 (12.
c5 bxc5 (12... Bd5) 13. bxc5 dxc5 14. dxc5 Ndxc5 15. Bb2 {White has more than
enough compensation for the pawn. Black's extra pawn is useless on "c7," and
White has a tremendous initiative on the open files and diagonals.}) (12. Ne1 {
as always, when White's knight leaves "f3" we are bringing the queen into
action.} Qh4 13. f3 Ng5 14. Bd3 Rf6 15. Qf2 Qh5 {[%cal Rf6g6,Rg6h6]}) 12... Rf6
{There are some alternatives, but this is the most straightforward way to
continue} 13. d5 (13. c5 {as we said, this move is not dangerous for Black.}
Bd5 14. c6 Nf8 {[%cal Rf6h6]} 15. b5 {White didn't achieve anything by
advancing his pawns} Rh6 {[%cal Rg7g5]} 16. Bc4 Qf6 17. Bxd5 exd5 {[%cal Rg7g5,
Rg5g4] with an attack}) 13... Rg6 (13... Rh6 {Usually this is the best square
for the rook} 14. dxe6 ({White can defend the pawn, but we are not planning to
take it anyway} 14. Rad1 c5 $1 {Smyslov's idea, covering the important "d4"
square.} 15. dxe6 Rxe6 16. bxc5 Ndxc5 (16... bxc5 $2 {usually we want to take
this way, but here this is a blunder due to:} 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Qb2+ Kg8 19.
Qxb7 $16) 17. Nd4 Rg6 {with an initiative} 18. Nxf5 $4 {is not working due to
the typical tactic} Rxg2+ 19. Kxg2 Qg5+ $19) (14. g3 c5 {is another way for
White to defend. Black should continue in a typical fashion:} 15. dxc6 (15.
dxe6 Rxe6 16. bxc5 Ndxc5 (16... bxc5 $2 17. Bxg7 $16) (16... dxc5 $5)) 15...
Bxc6 16. Nd4 $4 {This move is a blunder, and I want to show you another
typical tactic} Qh4 $3 17. gxh4 (17. Nf3 Qh3 $1 (17... Ng5 $1)) 17... Rg6+ 18.
Kh1 Nxf2# (18... Ng3+ 19. Kg1 Nxe2#)) 14... Rxe6 15. Nd4 Rg6) (13... e5 $2 {
This move looks logical, but it is a mistake.} 14. Nh4 $3 {after this move,
White has an advantage. The game can continue} g6 15. f4 Rf7 16. Nf3 Qe7 17.
Bd3 exf4 18. exf4 {The weakness of the long diagonal is decisive}) 14. Ne1 (14.
Rad1 {is well met with the typical} c5 15. Rfe1 (15. dxc6 Bxc6 16. Nd4 $4 Rxg2+
$19) (15. dxe6 Rxe6 16. bxc5 Ndxc5 (16... bxc5 {fails due to} 17. Bxg7 Rg6 18.
Ba1 $16) 17. Nd4 Rg6 {the greedy} 18. Nxf5 $4 {loses immediately} (18. Bf3 $11)
18... Rxg2+ 19. Kxg2 Qg5+ 20. Kh1 (20. Kh3 Qxf5+ 21. Bg4 Ng5+) 20... Nxf2#) (
15. bxc5 Ndxc5 $1 $17) 15... exd5 16. cxd5 Rc8 $11) (14. Nd4 {gives White an
advantage}) 14... Qg5 15. f4 Qe7 16. Nf3 c5 17. dxc6 (17. dxe6 Qxe6 18. bxc5
bxc5 $1 (18... Ndxc5 $15) 19. Rad1 Bc6 $15 {This is an important construction
to remember. White can't penetrate on the queenside, and we can concentrate on
the kingside.}) 17... Bxc6 18. Nd4 Bb7 $15 {The position is close to equal,
but I prefer Black here. Smyslov manages to win the game later} 19. Bf3 Rc8 20.
Rac1 a6 21. Qd3 Ndf6 22. Rc2 h5 23. Nb3 h4 24. Bxf6 Qxf6 25. Nd2 d5 26. cxd5
Rxc2 27. Qxc2 exd5 28. Bxe4 dxe4 29. Nb3 h3 30. g3 Qf7 31. Nd4 Rd6 32. Rc1 Kh7
33. Qe2 Rd8 34. Qf1 Qh5 35. Rc7 Bc8 36. Qa1 Qg4 37. Kf2 Be6 38. Ke1 Rd6 39. Qd1
Qg6 40. Qc2 Bd7 41. Ra7 Bb5 42. a4 Bd3 1/2-1/2

