{[%evp 0,32,24,24,25,-23,-7,-1,43,21,25,-1,9,9,5,5,5,5,5,14,22,11,18,12,17,4,
17,2,35,35,27,15,15,-62,0] In the following example we will see the systems
with g3. This is a different approach from the -e3 systems. The biggest
difference is that White's king is quite safe, and the game is quite
positional. The bishop is defending the king, but on the other hand, he is not
influencing the centre and the queenside that much. Black should follow the
scheme: Bb7, 0-0 and then a5, Bxd2, d6, Be4, etc...} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. g3 Bb7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O (7. a3 {Black wants to take on d2
anyway, so I think this is just a waste of time} Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 a5 9. b3 {
Very often White is trying not to allow a5-a4} ({of course} 9. b4 $2 {is just
bad due to} axb4 {and White is forced to take with the queen} 10. Qxb4 $15)
9... d6 10. Bb2 (10. d5 exd5 11. Nh4 Ne4) 10... Nbd7 11. O-O Be4 $1 12. Rfd1
Qb8 $1 {when White's pawns on the queenside are a bit soft (b3,a3) the idea of
Qb8 is quite attractive} 13. Rac1 b5 14. cxb5 (14. c5 {is never dangerous for
Black} Nd5 15. e3 f5 16. Ng5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qe8 18. cxd6 (18. c6 N7f6) 18...
cxd6) 14... Qxb5 15. Rxc7 Qxb3 $15) 7... a5 $1 {I think this is the best move
order for Black. Our next moves will be Bxd2, d6, Be4, etc..} (7... Bxd2 8.
Bxd2 Be4 $1 (8... d6 $6 9. Bc3 (9. b4 $3 {Remember this idea. On the contrary
to the e3-systems, here, the idea of quick b4 is quite strong. White is fixing
the pawn on a7 and is ready to met a5 with bxa5. He is planning to continue
with a4-a5 with serious pressure on the queenside.} Nbd7 10. a4 Ne4 {will be
easily met with} (10... Qe7 {is also not solving the problems} 11. a5 Be4 12.
Qb3 $14 {[%cal Ra1a3,Rf1a1]}) 11. Be1 ({or} 11. Ng5)) 9... Nbd7 (9... Be4 10.
d5) 10. d5 exd5 11. Nh4) 9. b4 $1 d6 10. a4 Nbd7 (10... a6 11. Qb3 Nbd7 12. a5
b5 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Rfc1 $16) 11. a5) (7... d6 8. Nb1
{We should always be ready for this move. In this particular case, Black is
just fine after:} (8. a3 $5 {is possible} Bxd2 9. Bxd2 Nbd7 10. b4 $14) 8... d5
9. c5 bxc5 10. a3 Ba5 11. dxc5 c6 12. b4 Bc7 13. Bb2 Nbd7 $11 {Black is just
fine}) 8. a3 (8. Qc2 Bxd2 9. Bxd2 (9. Nxd2 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Nc6 11. e3 d5 12. cxd5
Qxd5+ 13. Kg1 Nb4 14. Qd1 c5 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. a3 Nc6 (16... Nd3)) 9... Be4 10.
Qc1 d6 {This is a very specific position for this line. So I will check
several possible plans for White.} 11. Bf4 (11. Bc3 Nbd7 12. Bh3 h6 13. Nd2 Bb7
(13... Bh7) 14. f3 {we should never allow White to have e4, d4, c4 center.} Re8
$6 (14... c5 15. e4 cxd4 16. Bxd4 Rc8 {This Hedgehog position is also quite
playable for Black}) (14... d5 $5 15. cxd5 exd5 (15... Nxd5 16. e4 Nxc3 17.
Qxc3 c5 {Black has counterplay}) 16. Re1 c5 17. dxc5 Nxc5 (17... bxc5 18. Bxf6
Nxf6 19. Qxc5)) (14... e5 15. d5 e4 (15... c6 16. e4) 16. Bxd7 Nxd7 17. Nxe4)
15. e4 $14) (11. a3 Nbd7 (11... a4) 12. b4 h6 13. Qc3 axb4 14. axb4 b5) (11. b3
Nbd7 12. a3 h6 $5 13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 b5 15. c5 Nd5 16. Qb2 f5) 11... Nbd7 12.
Bh3 Re8 13. Nd2 Bb7 14. Be3 h6 (14... c5) 15. f3 c5 16. Qc3 (16. dxc5 bxc5 17.
Rd1 d5 $17) (16. Bf2 d5 17. cxd5 Nxd5 18. e4 (18. dxc5) 18... Nb4) 16... d5 (
16... e5 $2 17. d5 e4 18. f4 (18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. fxe4)) 17. Rfd1 (17. dxc5 bxc5
18. cxd5 exd5) 17... e5 18. dxe5 d4 19. Qc1 Nxe5 20. Bf4 Ng6) (8. Nb1 {As we
mentioned, this move is always an idea, but usually it is stronger when Black
has a pawn on d6.} Be7 9. Nc3 Ne4 (9... Bb4 {is another possible way to
continue} 10. Bd2 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Be4) 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Be4) (8. Re1 Bxd2 (
8... Ne4) (8... d6 9. e4 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Bxe1 11. Qxe1) (8... d5 $5) 9. Bxd2 Be4
10. Bf1 (10. b3 d6 11. Bc3 Nbd7 12. a3 Qb8) 10... h6 11. Nh4 d5 (11... Bb7 12.
f3 d5 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Rc1 Nbd7 15. Ng2 c5 16. dxc5 bxc5 (16... Nxc5 17. Bc3
Re8)) 12. cxd5 exd5 (12... Bxd5 13. f3 Bb7 14. Bc3 (14. e3 Nbd7) 14... Nd5 15.
e4 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Nd7) 13. Rc1 Nbd7 14. f3 Bh7) 8... Bxd2 9. Bxd2 (9. Nxd2 {
is quite harmless} Bxg2 10. Kxg2 d5 $1 {followed by a4 and Black has a great
game}) 9... a4 $1 {fixing the structure} (9... Be4 $5 {is possible too}) (9...
Ne4 $6 {As a rule, this move is just pointless}) 10. Bg5 (10. Bc3 Be4 11. Qd2
d6 12. Rac1 Nbd7 13. Rfd1 {Black is totally fine here. There are several
possible plans for Black.} h6 {is always useful for Black in such positiions} (
13... d5 $5) (13... Qe7 $5) (13... c6 $5) (13... Qb8 {is another good move
with the idea b5} 14. h3 b5 15. cxb5 Qxb5 $11) 14. Bf1 c6 (14... d5 15. Ne5)
15. Ne1 d5 (15... d5) (15... b5 16. cxb5 cxb5 17. f3) 16. cxd5 cxd5) 10... d6
11. d5 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nd4 exd5 14. cxd5 {Such structure is usually
favourable for White, but in this particular position, we have a fantastic
square for our knight.} Nd7 15. Rc1 Nc5 16. e3 Rae8 $11 *

