{[%evp 0,60,27,32,30,-3,-10,0,42,28,32,38,35,30,21,-8,0,7,9,-7,18,16,0,18,9,8,
17,14,22,1,16,-10,-3,-13,-20,-26,-23,-41,-53,-64,-2,-71,-77,-64,-55,-37,-63,
-87,-87,-87,-63,-87,-28,-8,-8,0,61,0,0,0,36,0,0]} 1. d4 {In this game we will
see why quick b4-advance is not good for Black.} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4.
Nbd2 d6 (4... b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. e3 O-O 8. b4 $6 {very typical
mistake which even very strong grandmaster including Carlsen committed. It is
too early for this move. Black should immediately strike with a5 intending the
exchange axb4, axb4, Rxa1. The rule is that this exchange is good for White
only if he can answer it with Rxa1. In the current position, White is quite
behind in development and Black can develop a serious initiative} a5 9. Bb2 (9.
b5 {is a concession. Now Black can start his play on the queenside when White
has no counterplay on the queenside.} d6 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. Be2 Qe7 12. O-O Ne4
13. Qc2 f5 14. d5 (14. c5 {is just dropping the pawn without compensation} bxc5
15. dxc5 Ndxc5 $15) 14... e5 15. Rfd1 Ndc5 $15) 9... axb4 10. axb4 Rxa1+ 11.
Bxa1 Qe7 (11... Ne4 $1 12. Qc2 Qe7 {White starts experiencing difficulties
defending the "b4" pawn. Black has the initiative here.} 13. c5 f5 14. Be2 Nc6
15. b5 Nb4 $15) 12. Be2 Nc6 13. b5 Ra8 14. O-O Nb4 $15) 5. e3 O-O 6. a3 Bxd2+
7. Qxd2 (7. Bxd2 Ne4 {Do you remember Capablanca's method. It is working well
here as well.} 8. Bd3 Nxd2 9. Qxd2 Qe7 10. O-O (10. e4 e5 11. d5 a5 $15) 10...
e5 $11) 7... Nbd7 8. b4 $2 a5 9. b5 ({Of course} 9. Bb2 {is possible, but
Black has a good game after} axb4 10. axb4 Rxa1+ 11. Bxa1 b5 $1 $36) 9... b6
10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O Ne4 12. Qc2 f5 13. Bb2 (13. Ne1 {We already know that when
the knight leaves f3 we should play} Qh4 $1) (13. Nd2 Qh4 14. Nxe4 fxe4 $1 {
[%cal Rf8f5,Rf8f6,Rf6h6] It looks weird at first, but now we cut the board on
two and we can easily organize an attack against White's king.} (14... Bxe4 $6
{looks natural, but actually is not the best move here. Too many pieces are
exhanged and Black's attack is not that dangerous.} 15. Qd2 Rf6 16. f3 Rh6 17.
h3 Bb7 18. Qe1 $11) 15. Bb2 Rf6 $17) 13... Rf6 14. d5 Rh6 ({The natural} 14...
e5 $2 {is a mistake due to} 15. Nh4 $1 $16) 15. g3 (15. Nd4 $2 Qh4 16. h3 Ng5
$19) 15... Ndc5 16. Rad1 Qe7 17. Nd4 Qg5 18. Kg2 ({if White is not careful and
play a random move like} 18. a4 {Black should continue with} Rf8 $1 {and have
the idea Nxg3 in mind}) 18... Rf8 19. Rh1 exd5 (19... e5 {Blocking the
dark-squared bishop gives Black an advantage.}) 20. Nf3 Qh5 21. cxd5 Qh3+ 22.
Kg1 Rg6 23. Bf1 Qh5 24. Be2 Qh3 ({I missed the strong} 24... f4 $1 25. exf4
Rxf4 $17 {with a crushing attack}) 25. Bf1 Qh6 26. Bg2 Qh5 27. Nh4 Rg5 28. Nf3
Rg6 29. Nh4 Rg5 30. Nf3 Rg6 1/2-1/2

