{[%evp 0,27,12,18,18,16,16,16,29,20,20,21,21,9,7,13,2,5,3,4,-8,-12,-6,6,2,0,0,
-8,0,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 O-O 7.
e3 Bb7 8. b4 $6 {amazing that even the strongest player in the world make such
mistake} a5 9. Bb2 (9. b5 {is similar to my game with Loek van Wely} d6 10. a4
Nbd7 11. Be2 Ne4 12. Qc2 f5 13. O-O Rf6 14. d5 Rh6 15. Bb2 e5 $15) 9... axb4
10. axb4 Ne4 11. Qc2 Rxa1+ 12. Bxa1 Qe7 13. c5 (13. Bc3 Na6 (13... f5 {is also
possible and good} 14. Be2 Nc6 15. b5 Nb4 16. Qb2 Nxc3 17. Qxc3 Ra8 18. O-O Na2
{[%cal Rb7e4,Re7b4] with an initiative for Black}) ({The simplest} 13... Nxc3
14. Qxc3 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nc6 16. b5 Nb4 $11 {equalizes for Black too}) {and if}
14. b5 $4 (14. c5 $1) 14... Nb4 15. Qb2 Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Ra8 17. Be2 Ra3 $19)
13... f5 14. Be2 {[%cal Rb7d5,Rb6c5,Rb8c6]} Nc6 $2 15. Bc3 bxc5 (15... Ra8 16.
O-O Qd8) 16. dxc5 Ra8 17. O-O Nxc3 18. Qxc3 $16 {Carlsen gets the advantage
and manages to win the game} Qf6 19. Qd2 Rd8 20. b5 Ne5 21. Nxe5 Qxe5 22. c6
Bc8 23. Rd1 d5 24. Qd4 Qxd4 25. exd4 Kf8 26. f4 Ke7 27. Ra1 g6 28. Kf2 Kd6 29.
Ra3 Rf8 30. h4 Ke7 31. h5 Rg8 32. hxg6 hxg6 33. Rh3 g5 34. fxg5 Kd6 35. Rh6 Ke7
36. Bf3 e5 37. Rh7+ Kd6 38. dxe5+ Kc5 39. Rxc7 Kxb5 40. Bxd5 1-0

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bogo-Indian 4.Bd2 Qe7"]
[Black "Theoretical Suggestions"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E11"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "40"]

{In general, in Bogo-Indian, the plans are much more important than the
concrete theory. Nevertheless, in this file I will give you some directions
and will mention some important moments.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2
Qe7 {White's main line is 5.g3. White has some other options at his disposal,
but against all of them we can just take on "d2" and play d6-e5!} 5. g3 (5. a3
Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 (6. Nbxd2 $6 {As we know from the lecture about the pawn
structure, it is always preferable to take with the queen on "d2"} d6 7. e3 e5
$36) 6... d6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. e4 e5 9. d5 a5 $36 {with an easy game for Black}) ({
Against moves like} 5. e3 {we do not need to know any concrete theory, but
just follow the well know plan: Bxd2, followed by d6 and e5.} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 (6.
Nbxd2 $6 d6 {[%cal Re6e5]}) 6... d6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 $132 c6 $1 (8... e5 $36
9. O-O e4 10. Ne1 c6 $132 11. Nc2 Bf5) 9. O-O e5) ({It is possible to start
with} 5. Nc3 {but then Black can follow Capablanca's idea} Bxc3 $5 6. Bxc3 Ne4
7. Qc2 Nxc3 8. Qxc3 O-O (8... b6 $5 {is also playable} 9. e4 Bb7 10. Bd3 d6
$132) 9. e4 d6 10. Be2 Nd7 11. O-O e5 $132 {Black has nothing to worry about})
{The best move in this position is} 5... Nc6 {The idea of this move is quite
concrete. It initiates a small tactic. After 5...Nc6 6.Bg2 is not very good.} (
{I drew against Carlsen with} 5... Bxd2+ {but objectively, this is another
type of position and it is risky for Black.} 6. Qxd2 $1 (6. Nbxd2 $2 d6 {
is just very good for Black}) 6... Ne4 {now this is pointless} 7. Qc2 Qb4+ 8.
Nbd2 Nxd2 9. Nxd2 $14) 6. Nc3 $1 {This is the best move!} (6. Bg2 $6 {this is
the most common move and yet it is clearly not the best! Now Black gets a very
nice game! The correct move is 6.Nc3!} Bxd2+ $1 7. Nbxd2 {White is almost
forced to make a concession and to take with the knight on d2. We discussed
this position in the lecture about plans.} (7. Qxd2 $6 Ne4 8. Qc2 Qb4+ 9. Kf1
$5 {in fact, this has been played by a few GMs and it is not so bad! Black
still gets a good game!} (9. Nbd2 $6 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 (10. Nxd2 Nxd4) 10... Qxc4
11. O-O Qb4 $3 $15 12. Qf4 (12. Qc2 d5) 12... d6 $17) (9. Nc3 $6 {For some
reason, many good players enter this position with White. I think that Black
is just better here.} Nxc3 10. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 11. bxc3 Rb8 12. O-O (12. c5 b6 13.
cxb6 axb6 (13... cxb6 $15)) 12... b6 $15 {Black has a safe square on "e7" for
his king and better pawn structure.} (12... d6 $15) (12... Ke7 $15)) 9... f5 $1
{the engines initially don't like this move, but in fact, this is the best
continuation for Black.} 10. a3 Qe7 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. Qxc3 O-O 13. e3 d6 {
weak engines suggests some rubbish move like} 14. h4 {saying that White has a
small advantage, but this is not true and Black is just fine after the natural:
} (14. Kg1 e5 15. d5 Nb8 $1 $15 (15... Nd8 $5 $15) 16. h3 a5 17. b3 Nd7 18. Kh2
g5 $17) 14... e5 15. b4 e4 16. Nd2 a5 $36) 7... d6 $1 {all these moves are
good and they more or less lead to the same positions. Now you do not need to
know any specific theory, but just to study the games and to understand the
ideas and the plans} (7... a5 $1) (7... O-O $1) 8. O-O a5 $1 (8... O-O $1 9. e4
e5 (9... a5 $1 10. e5) 10. d5 Nb8 11. Ne1 {This is White's best plan} a5 12.
Nd3 Na6 13. a3 (13. f4 $6 {is not dangerous at all} Nd7 (13... Nb4) 14. f5 f6
15. g4 Ndc5 $15 16. Nxc5 Nxc5 17. Rf3 Bd7 18. Qe2 Rfb8 $17 (18... a4 $5)) 13...
c6 (13... Bg4 14. f3 Bd7 15. b3 c6 $36)) 9. e4 (9. Rc1 {Is possible but
doesn't pose any problems for Black.} O-O 10. e4 e5 11. d5 Nb4 {as we said,
this move is only working when it comes with tempo.} 12. a3 Nd3 13. Rc3 Nc5 $15
14. Re1 a4 $17 15. h3 Bd7 $15 {intending b5} (15... c6 {this typical move is
also good here} 16. Qe2 cxd5 17. cxd5 Bd7)) (9. e3 e5 10. Rc1 O-O 11. b3 e4 {
Light-squared strategy} (11... Bg4 12. d5 Nb8 13. h3 Bd7 14. e4 Na6 15. Ne1 c6)
12. Ng5 (12. Nh4 g5 $19) 12... Bf5 $15 13. a3 h6 14. Nh3 Nb8 15. Nf4 c6 $17)
9... e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. Ne1 (11. b3 {is possible, but now we proceed with} O-O
12. a3 Na6 13. Qc2 c6 14. Rfe1 cxd5 15. cxd5 b5 $1 {taking control of the
important c4-square} 16. Rac1 Bd7 $15 17. Qb2 Qd8 $3 18. h3 Qb6 $36) 11... O-O
$1 (11... h5 $1 {The plans with an early h5 are quite interesting. I include
some examples in the game section!}) 12. Nd3 Na6 13. a3 c6 14. b4 cxd5 15. cxd5
(15. exd5 $4 Bf5 16. Nb3 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 axb4 $19) 15... axb4 16. axb4 Bg4 $15
17. f3 (17. Bf3 Bd7) 17... Bd7 18. Qb3 Nc7 $3 $17 19. Rfc1 Nb5 20. Qb2 h5 $17 (
20... Nd4)) (6. a3 $6 {is waste of time} Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8. Bg2 e5 9. d5 Nb8
10. e4 O-O 11. O-O a5 12. b4 Na6 13. Rb1 axb4 14. axb4 c6 15. Re1 cxd5 16. cxd5
Bd7 $132) 6... Bxc3 $1 {the most reliable way .. in the style of Capablanca! ..
.first, give the bishop for the knight...and then give the knight for the
bishop!!! (PAP)} 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8. Rc1 (8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 O-O $1 (9... Qb4 $5
$11) 10. Bg2 d6 11. O-O (11. d5 Nd8 $132) 11... e5 (11... a5 $132) 12. d5 Nb8
13. e4 Nd7 $132) (8. Bg2 $2 Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. O-O d6 $15 {is already better
for Black due to the better pawn structure}) (8. Bd2 $6 Nxd2 (8... f5 $5 $132)
9. Qxd2 O-O 10. Bg2 d6 11. O-O e5 (11... a5 $132 {is probably even more
accurate}) 12. d5 Nb8 $36 (12... Nd8 {[%cal Rf7f5,Rd8f7]}) 13. e4 a5 (13... f5
{maybe b5 is also possible})) 8... O-O $1 {be careful with the move order 8...
0-0! is more accurate because after 8...d6 there is 9. d5! with some advantage
for White! However, in the game section, you will see that way too many strong
players have committed this small mistake!} (8... d6 $6 9. d5 Nxc3 10. Rxc3 Nd8
11. dxe6 $14 {I prefer White here}) 9. Bg2 (9. d5 $6 {runs to} Qc5 $1 (9...
Nxc3) 10. e3 Nb4 11. Qb3 Nxc3 12. Rxc3 a5 $132) 9... d6 10. O-O {This is the
main theoretical position} (10. d5 $1 {by a different move order we reach the
game Ivanchuk-Papaioannou 2011 (1/2-1/2) where Black had good counter chances
but white objectively might by slightly better} Nd8 $1 (10... Nxc3 $6 {this is
not working here because White is just on time to take de6 after Nb8. If Black
goes Nd8 after taking on c3, then White will probably just castle and if e6-e5,
then we have a passive game with the knight on d8 instead of b8!} 11. Rxc3 Nb8
(11... Nd8 12. O-O $14) 12. dxe6 $14) 11. O-O (11. dxe6) 11... f5 $5 (11... e5
$5 {this is the suggestion of GM Marin .. and Black gets interesting counter
play} 12. Be1 (12. c5 $5 {is still very interesting, but Black is not force to
take the pawn and can proceed with} f5 $1 13. cxd6 cxd6 14. Bb4 (14. Nd2 Nxc3 (
14... Nf6 $5 15. Nc4 Nf7 $11 {The knight is well placed on f7 in these systems}
) 15. Rxc3 Nf7 $13) 14... Nf7 $132) (12. Nd2 {is possible, but Black can
proceed with} Nxc3 13. Rxc3 b6 14. b4 a5 15. a3 axb4 16. axb4 f5 $36) 12... a5
$1 (12... f5 $1 {is also possible} 13. Nd2 Nf6 $1 $36) 13. Nd2 Nc5) 12. dxe6
Nxe6 13. Nd4 (13. Be1 $6 a5 14. e3 b6 15. b3 Bb7 $15) 13... N6g5 $5 {
Ivanchuk-Papaioannou 2011} (13... Nxd4 $5 14. Qxd4 a5 15. Rfd1 Qf7 16. e3 b6
$132 17. Qd5 Be6 $11)) 10... e5 $1 {is a very good idea without much theory!} (
10... Nxc3 $5 {Is the main line} 11. Rxc3 e5 12. d5 Nb8 13. c5 $1 {with a lot
of theory ! White's rook is perfectly played on c3. White is ready to triple
his major pieces on c-file.}) 11. Be1 (11. d5 $5 Nb8 ({another option is} 11...
Nxc3 12. Rxc3 Nb8 $13) ({very interesting is also} 11... Nd8 12. Be1 f5 13. Nd2
Nf6 $1 {typical idea. Black avoids exchanges and is planning to play on the
kingside}) 12. Be1 a5 $1 13. Nd2 Nxd2 (13... Nc5 $5 14. Nb3 Nxb3 (14... b6 $132
) 15. axb3 b6 16. Ra1 Na6) 14. Bxd2 Nd7 15. e4 Nc5 16. Be3 b6 $36) (11. dxe5 $2
{is wrong due to the intermediate} Nxc3 $1 12. Rxc3 dxe5 $15 13. Nd2 Bg4 $3 {
we are not afraid of} 14. Bxc6 $2 bxc6 {because White's king will be weak, but
also because Black's double pawns are on a closed file and White can't attack
them.}) (11. Nxe5 $4 {is losing by force, but you need to memorize some lines}
Nxc3 12. Nxc6 Nxe2+ 13. Kh1 bxc6 14. Re1 Re8 $3 15. Bxc6 (15. Rc2 Nxg3+ $19) (
15. Bf3 Qf6 16. Bxe2 Qxf2 $19 17. Bf1 Bd7 $19) 15... Rb8 $3 $19 16. Bxe8 Qe4+
17. f3 Qxf3#) (11. e3 $6 {is totally sensless and just waste of time} Nxc3 $5 (
11... f5 $5 $132) 12. Rxc3 a5 $132 13. d5 Nb4 14. a3 Na6 $15 15. e4 Nc5 16. Nd2
a4 $17 {with a strategically winning position for Black.} 17. f4 Bd7 18. f5 f6
19. g4 b5 $17) 11... f5 12. d5 (12. e3 {is something we shouldn't be afraid of}
a5 13. b3 Nf6 $36 (13... Bd7 $36 {[%cal Rg8h8]}) 14. Bc3 e4 $1 {light-squared
strategy in action} 15. Nd2 d5 16. c5 g5 $40) 12... Nd8 $1 {this time Nd8 is
good because it is followed by a very fast Nf7!} 13. Nd2 (13. b4 Nf7 14. c5 b6
$132 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Nd2 Nf6 $1 $15 {again this typical idea, we are not
exchanging Black's passive pieces} 17. b5 Bd7 18. a4 f4 $36) 13... Nf6 $3 14.
b4 Nf7 15. c5 f4 $1 $36 {Black starts a serious attack} 16. Nc4 b5 $1 {is a
good suggestion by the engine} (16... Ng5 $15) 17. Na5 Ng5 18. Nc6 Qf7 $17 19.
h4 Nh3+ 20. Kh1 Bd7 $17 (20... g5 $5) *

