1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Qe7 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8.
O-O O-O 9. Qc2 {this is a natural move, but not a theoretical one. Now we
should just follow our plan.} a5 $1 {This move is useful in any case.} 10. Qc3
e5 $1 {you shouldn't hesitate to play e5!} 11. d5 Nb8 12. e4 Nbd7 $132 {
White played natural-looking moves, but the position is already preferable for
Black.} (12... Na6 {is usually better than Nd7, but here the a5-pawn is
hanging.} 13. Qxa5) 13. Ne1 Nc5 14. Nc2 $6 (14. Nd3 Nfd7 15. f4 Nxd3 16. Qxd3
Nc5 17. Qe3 Bd7 $1 {as so often, we allow white to play f4-f5  because he is
slow with his flank attack due to the absence of dark-square bishops! Black
has a fast and active play on the other side! However, after the f4 move by
White, we should always consider ef4! which quite often gives us great play!}
18. f5 f6 $1 19. g4 b5 $15 (19... c6 $15 20. h4 b5 21. dxc6 Bxc6 22. cxb5 Bxb5)
{Let's see how the game can continue} 20. h4 bxc4 21. Nxc4 Bb5 22. Rfc1 Bxc4
23. Rxc4 Rfb8 24. Rc2 Rb4 $17 {[%cal Ra8b8] Black wants to force b2-b3 and
then attack the queenside with a4}) 14... c6 $1 $15 (14... h5 $5 {as so often
in such positions, the computer is screaming for h7-h5! However, in this
particular position, I would call it an unnecessary risk!} 15. h4 Ng4 16. Ne3
g6 $36) 15. b3 cxd5 16. exd5 (16. cxd5 b5 $15 (16... Bd7 $15)) 16... Bf5 $5 (
16... Bd7 $5 17. Rfe1 Bf5 $3 (17... b5)) (16... h5 $1) 17. a3 b5 $6 (17... Bg6
18. b4 Nd3 $36) 18. cxb5 Bd3 19. a4 $3 Bxf1 20. Rxf1 Qc7 21. Nc4 (21. Ne3 $1
$14) 21... Nfd7 22. N2e3 f5 23. f4 Ne4 24. Qc2 Qc5 25. Kh1 exf4 26. Nxf5 Rxf5
27. Qxe4 Rf6 28. gxf4 Qb4 29. Qe7 Nc5 30. Rg1 Raf8 31. Bh3 g6 32. Nxd6 Qxb3 33.
Ne8 R6f7 34. Qxc5 Qxh3 0-1

