1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Nf3 (6. e3 $5 {[%cal
Rg1e2]} Bxd2+) 6... Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 d6 8. e4 O-O 9. O-O e5 10. d5 (10. dxe5 dxe5
$17 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rc8g4]}) 10... Nb8 11. Ne1 (11. b4 a5 12. a3 Na6 13. Rb1 (
13. bxa5 Nc5 $15) (13. Qb3 c6 14. Rfc1 axb4 15. axb4 cxd5 16. cxd5 Bd7 $15)
13... c6 14. Ne1 cxd5 ({The other plan for Black is} 14... axb4 15. axb4 c5 16.
b5 Nb4 $15 {This plan is acceptable, but my practice proves that the position
is too closed and it is hard to play for a win with Black. Now the "c8" bishop
is equally bad as his colleague on "g2"}) 15. cxd5 axb4 16. axb4 Bd7 {Black
plans to put a piece on b5, he can choose which one the bishop or the knight.}
17. Nd3 $2 Nc7 $3 $17 18. Qb3 Nb5 19. Qb2 Nd4 20. Rfe1 Bb5 $19 {we can see now
when the queenside is open that our bishop is much better than his colleague
on g2.} 21. Bf1 h5 $5 22. h3 (22. h4 {the problem with this move is that f2-f4
is not good anymore.}) 22... h4 23. g4 {[%cal Rg7g5]} Nh7 {[%cal Rh7g5]}) 11...
a5 12. Nd3 Bg4 13. f3 Bd7 14. b3 Na6 15. a3 c6 16. dxc6 Bxc6 17. Qc2 b5 18.
Rfc1 Rfb8 19. Kh1 Nd7 20. Bf1 b4 21. axb4 Nxb4 22. Qc3 Nc5 23. Nxc5 dxc5 24.
Be2 Rd8 25. Nf1 f5 26. exf5 e4 27. f6 gxf6 28. Re1 Qe5 29. Rac1 Na2 30. Qxe5
fxe5 31. Ra1 exf3 32. Bxf3 Bxf3+ 33. Kg1 Nb4 34. Rxe5 Nd3 35. Rg5+ Kh8 36. Nd2
Bc6 {0-1 (36) Ippolito,D (2280)-Benjamin,J (2555) New York 1997} 0-1

