{[%evp 0,30,19,31,14,-14,3,5,26,17,27,30,32,-10,-8,9,20,-1,0,5,6,11,7,15,18,9,
20,3,12,-3,1,0,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 (5. e3 {
is a very interesting way to play with White} Bb7 6. Be2 {is harmless} (6. Bd3
c5 7. O-O (7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O {leads to Hedgehog as well}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4
O-O 9. a3 Be7 10. b4 $6 {is a typical mistake when the pawn is still on d7} a5
$1 (10... d5 $2 11. c5 $1 $16) 11. Rb1 (11. b5 d5 {and White can't play c5
anymore} 12. Bb2 Nbd7) 11... axb4 12. axb4 Nc6 13. b5 Nb4 14. Be2 d5 $17) 6...
c5 $1 7. dxc5 {this move leads to hedgehog types of positions after} (7. O-O
cxd4 8. exd4 O-O 9. a3 Be7 10. b3 d5 11. Bb2 dxc4 (11... Nc6 $1 12. Rc1 dxc4
13. bxc4 Re8 {[%cal Re7f8,Rg7g6,Rf8g7]}) 12. bxc4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6a5,Rc6d4]
White's centre is vulnerable and Black can continue developing. It is hard to
suggest a good plan for White here.} (12... Nbd7 $6 {we never put the knight
on d7, because it is very passive there and not attacking the centre})) 7...
Bxc5 8. O-O O-O 9. b3 Be7 10. Bb2 d6 11. Rc1 Nbd7 {[%cal Ra7a6,Rd8c7,Rf8e8]
with a double-edged position}) (5. g3 Bb7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O a5 (7... d5 {
is transposing to Catalan, but I find this position quite hard to play for a
win}) 8. a3 Bxd2 9. Qxd2 Be4 {[%cal Rd7d6,Rb8d7,Rd8e7] with a double-edged game
}) 5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 (6. Nxd2 Bb7 7. f3 d5 (7... c5) (7... Nc6) 8. cxd5 exd5)
6... Bb7 7. e3 O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O a5 $1 {This is the most precise and
objectively the best way to play the position. White might be slightly better
but Black is very solid. He is ready to hit back with ...Ne4 and ...f7-f5
ideas or with play in the center by means of ...c7-c5 or ...e6-e5.} ({The main
alternative is} 9... Nbd7 10. b4 Ne4 {Although this system is a bit risky,
it's very interesting and playable.} (10... a5 $5 {is a good waiting move} 11.
Bb2 Qe7 12. Rfc1 Ne4 $5 {Whenever the f1-rook leaves it's spot, the idea ...
Ne4 followed by ...f7-f5 works very well for Black.} (12... Ra7 {[%cal Gf8a8]
is another typical idea. Black is ready to double on the a-file} 13. Qd1 axb4
14. axb4 Rfa8 15. Rxa7 Rxa7 16. Ra1 Rxa1 17. Qxa1 Qe8 $11) 13. Qc2 f5 $132) 11.
Qc2 f5 12. Bb2 {The main move for White.} ({In general,} 12. d5 $5 {is well
met by} e5 {[%cal Gc7c6] and ...c7-c6 is coming on the next move.} 13. Nd2 $1 {
This is the best for White} (13. Bd3 $6 {is not very good due to} c6 $3 14.
Bxe4 fxe4 15. Qxe4 cxd5 16. cxd5 Nf6 17. Qb1 Bxd5 18. Nd2 Qd7 $15 {In the
arising middlegame, Black is obviously better due to his superior bishop.}) ({
After} 13. Bb2 c6 $5 14. dxc6 Bxc6 15. Rad1 Qe7 $132 16. Rfe1 Rf6 {[%csl Gd6,
Ge5,Gf5] Remember this central pawn formation. The white minor pieces are
completely restricted. Additionally, Black has good attacking chances on the
kingside.}) 13... c6 14. Nxe4 ({An important detail is that after} 14. dxc6
Bxc6 15. Nxe4 {Black should recapture with the pawn} fxe4 $1 $132 {The e-pawn
divides the board into 2 parts and provides space advantage. The white pieces
cannot easily join the defence.}) 14... fxe4 15. Qxe4 cxd5 16. cxd5 Nf6 17. Qc2
Bxd5 18. Bb2 Qd7 $5 $132 {Black has very good counterplay.}) 12... Rf6 13. d5 {
The most principled move.} ({Against slow moves such as} 13. Rad1 {we should
put the rook on g6 -} Rg6 $1 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gg6g2,Gb7g2] The pressure on g2
is very annoying.}) 13... Rh6 $1 {Black should always put the rook on h6 in
response to d4-d5.} ({This time,} 13... Rg6 {runs into} 14. Nd4 {with an
obvious advantage for White.}) 14. g3 ({After} 14. dxe6 Rxe6 15. Nd4 Rg6 {
Black has excellent attacking chances.}) ({A thematic idea is to answer} 14.
Rad1 {with} c5 $1 15. dxc6 ({After} 15. dxe6 {Black should play} Rxe6 ({
The generally desirable} 15... Nf8 $6 {would be met by} 16. Be5) 16. bxc5 (16.
Rfe1 Qe7 17. bxc5 bxc5) 16... Ndxc5 $15 ({Attention! After} 16... bxc5 {
White has the thematic} 17. Bxg7 $16)) 15... Bxc6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 16. Nd4 Qh4
17. Nf3 Qh5 {Black's attack is potentially very dangerous.}) ({Contrary to the
position after ...Rg6, now} 14. Nd4 $2 {can be answered with} Qh4 {Whenever
the f3-knight goes somewhere, you need to add the queen to the attack.} 15. Nf3
Qh5 {Black is already a bit better.}) ({Another typical line is} 14. Rac1 c5 $1
15. dxe6 Rxe6 16. bxc5 ({Nothing gives} 16. Rfd1 {when Black can follow with}
Qe7 17. bxc5 bxc5 {[%csl Gb7,Gc5,Gd6] The formation Bb7 + d6 and c5 is very
strong since it control a lot of important squares.} 18. Ne1 {The knight
leaves the f3-square. So, Black immediately goes} Qh4) 16... Ndxc5 $1 17. Nd4
Rg6 18. Bf3 Qd7 $36 {Black can already overtake the initiative.}) (14. Rfd1 c5
$1) 14... c5 {Smyslov's idea} 15. Nd2 ({A very nice tactical idea can happen
after} 15. dxc6 Bxc6 16. Nd4 ({The slow} 16. Rfd1 {allows} e5 17. Rac1 Qe7 18.
a4 Rf8 19. a5 f4 {with an attack.}) 16... Qh4 $3 $19 {Remember this idea.
Black is winning on the spot.}) (15. Nh4 Qe7 $132 {The position is unclear and
playable for both colours.}) 15... exd5 16. cxd5 Qe7 {Black enjoys decent
counterplay.}) 10. b3 Nbd7 11. Bb2 Qe7 $132 12. Rfd1 $6 (12. Rac1 h6 {waiting
for Rfd1} ({or} 12... Rfd8 13. Rfd1 c5 $132 14. h3 h6 15. dxc5 Nxc5) 13. Rfd1
Ne4 14. Qc2 f5 {When White had already commited to Rfd1, the setup with ...
f7-f5 is always playable.}) 12... Ne4 $3 {It is a good idea to wait a bit and
only after the f1-rook moves to play ...Ne4 and ...f7-f5. The plan is more
effective that way.} 13. Qc2 f5 14. d5 (14. Nd2 Qh4 15. Nxe4 fxe4 $3 $15) 14...
e5 15. Rac1 c6 $36 {Black's position is already preferable.} *

