{In the final section of the camp database, I would like to provide a pretty
much universal opening system that can be used both in Bogo-Indian and
Nimzo-Indian. This is a repertoire that I have created for my students. To
build this scheme, I have borrowed ideas from different openings arising after
1...Nf6 and 2...e6. The first important point is that after} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
{[%cal Gf8b4] Black is planning to play ...Bb4 against pretty much everything.
The setup is very simple. After ...Bb4, we are ready to exchange this bishop
either for a bishop or a knight. Afterwards, Black follows with ...d7-d6, ...
0-0, ...Qe7, ...Nbd7, ...e6-e5, ...Re8, ...Nf8-g6. Strangely enough, this
setup works against pretty much everything. Since we have already studied the
Bogo-Indian Defence, in this section, I will mostly focus on examples taken
from the Nimzo-Indian Defence.} 3. Nc3 ({We can play in the same way after} 3.
Nf3 {Let's see one simple example -} Bb4+ {[%cal Gd8e7,Gd7d6,Ge8g8,Gb8d7,Gf8e8,
Ge6e5,Gd7f8,Gf8g6]} 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 Qe7 6. Nc3 d6 7. e4 e5 8. d5 O-O 9.
Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O Re8 11. Qc2 Nf8 12. b4 Ng6 {Black has achieved his desired
position. Later on, he will follow with ... Nh5-f4 followed by ...Rf8 and ...
f7-f5.}) 3... Bb4 {Sooner or later, Black will give his dark-squared bishop
for the knight. The question is whether White will accept double pawns or not.
For simplicity, I would advise you to double the opponent's pawns whenever
it's possible. For example, we play ... Bxc3 against 4.Nf3, 4.g3, 4.Bg5, and 4.
a3. If White plays 4.Bd2 or 4.Qc2, then we follow our usual setup with ...0-0,
...d7-d6, ...Qe7 and so on. Our approach is not optimal only against 4.e3 and
4.f3. Against these lines, you will probably need to learn an alternative
system. In the model games that follow, I take examples from different lines
in Nimzo-Indian Defence. The games are taken from the practice of my students.}
*

