-275,-283,-298,-297,-293,-295,-302,-198,-204,-146,-141,-137,-137,-151,-148,
-148,-185,-199,-204,-196,-207,-206,-224,-167] At the beginning, I shall
provide some model games in which White meets ...e6-e5 with dxe5, thus forcing
the transition into a symmetrical pawn structure. Since the model games have
been played by students of mine, the names of the players will not be
displayed.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 d6
7. Qc2 ({As we are going to witness on a number of occasions, the move} 7. Bg5
{should be met with} h6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 {When a typical position arises.}) 7...
Qe7 8. e4 e5 {You should always try to achieve this central tension.White
should be provoked to release the tension by means of d4-d5 or dxe5.} 9. dxe5 {
In general, the structure arising after this move is almost always favourable
for Black. In this model game, you will see how to fight for the d4-square.} ({
In case of} 9. d5 {we get the structure discussed in the Bogo-Indian section.
Here is a typical follow-up.} a5 10. b3 (10. Be2 a4 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Bb4 Re8
13. Rfe1 b6 $1 (13... Nf8 14. c5) 14. Nd2 Nc5) 10... Na6 11. b4 $2 (11. Bd3 Nc5
12. O-O Bg4 13. Ne1 a4 14. b4 Nb3 $15 {[%cal Gb3d4]}) 11... axb4 12. axb4 Nxb4
$19) 9... dxe5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8g4,Gb8c6] Black's main goal in this
position is to establish a strong control of the d4-square by playing moves
such as ...Nc6 and ...Bg4.} 10. c5 ({Another possibility is} 10. Be2 c5 11. O-O
Bg4 12. Bc3 Nc6) 10... Bg4 11. Be2 Nc6 12. Bc3 $4 {This is just dropping a
pawn. The remaining part of the game does not need comments.} ({After} 12. Be3
Rfd8 13. O-O Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Nd4 15. Bxd4 Rxd4 {we get a position that you
should remember. Black has full control of the d4-square and good
possibilities to play on the dark-squares. White's light-squared bishop is
completely useless.}) 12... Qxc5 13. b4 Qe7 14. Rc1 a6 15. O-O Rad8 16. Bb2 Rd7
17. Rfe1 Rfd8 18. Qc3 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Nd4 20. Bd1 c6 21. a4 h6 22. Ba3 Qe6 23. h3
b5 24. Ra1 bxa4 25. Bxa4 Nb5 26. Qb3 Qxb3 27. Bxb3 Rd3 28. Reb1 Nxe4 29. Bc2
Nxa3 30. Bxd3 Rxd3 31. Rc1 Nc3 {'} 32. Kh2 Ncb5 33. Rxc6 Rd2 34. Rxa6 Rxf2 35.
R1xa3 Nxa3 36. Rxa3 Rb2 37. Re3 f6 38. Re4 Kf7 39. Rc4 Ke6 40. Kg3 Kd5 {
