-177,-202,-220,-167,-178,-170,-183,-167,-186,-179,-178,-189,-369,-225,-238,
-216,-411,-357] Whenever White allows, Black should take the opportunity to
double the opponent's pawns by playing ...Bxc3. I would like to provide a few
model games that illustrate Black's ideas in such structures.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ $1 {Spoling White's pawn
structure.} 7. bxc3 d6 {[%cal Ge6e5] After giving the dark-squared bishop away,
it's very important to put all the pawns on dark squares.} 8. O-O e5 9. Be2 h6
{Making sure that White will never get rid of his dark-squared bishop by
playing Bg5. The advance ...h7-h6 is always useful in this pawn structure.} 10.
h3 O-O 11. a4 b6 12. Qc2 e4 $1 {[%csl Rc1] As it was the case in Bogo-Indian
positions, the advance ...e5-e4 marks the beginning of Black's light square
strategy. I remind you that this strategy is effective when White's
dark-squared bishop cannot enter the game.} 13. Nd2 Bf5 14. Ba3 Qe7 $17 {
White does not have any counterplay. On the other hand, Black is ready to
organize his kingside attack.} 15. Rfe1 Rfe8 16. f4 exf3 $1 ({Another typical
idea would have been} 16... h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gg8h8,Ge8g8,Gg7g5] with the
idea of ...h5-h4 followed by ...Kh8, ...Rg8 and ...g7-g5.}) 17. Qxf5 Qxe3+ 18.
Kh1 fxe2 $18 19. Nf3 Qe4 20. Qxe4 Rxe4 21. Ra2 Rae8 22. Ng1 Na5 23. Raxe2 Rxe2
24. Rxe2 Rxe2 25. Nxe2 Nxc4 26. Bc1 Nd5 27. g4 g6 28. dxc5 dxc5 29. Bxh6 Nb2
30. Bd2 f6 31. Kg2 Kf7 32. Kf3 Ke6 33. Ke4 Nxa4 34. c4 f5+ 35. Kd3 Nb4+ 36.
Bxb4 cxb4 37. g5 Nc5+ {White resigns.} *

