-18,-15,-60,-67,-78,-39,-71,-65,-71,-71,-71,-71,-84,-91,-221,-227,-307,-307,
-29997,-29998] Another Nimzo-Indian system which is well met by our special
line is the system with 4.Bg5. Let's take a look at an instructive example.} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 h6 6. Bxf6 {Giving the
dark-squared bishop away is always harmless.} ({After} 6. Bh4 {Black should
follow the same concept. I would like to provide just an exemplary line -} d6
7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. e4 Qe7 9. Nf3 e5 10. Bd3 c5 $1 {Once again, I would like to
remind that this move is a very important part of our strategy.} 11. O-O {
This time White prefers to keep the tension.} ({After} 11. d5 {Black's scheme
is clear -} Nf8 12. O-O Ng6 ({An alternative is} 12... g5 13. Bg3 Ng6 14. Qa4+
Kf8 15. Rfe1 Bg4 {Black build a promising kingside attack. In this type of
position, the main idea is ...h5-h4.})) 11... O-O 12. Rfe1 Re8 13. Rad1 Nf8 {
Black follows exactly the same strategy. Despite the central tension. Because
of the move ...c7-c5, White cannot break in the centre.} 14. h3 Ng6 15. Bg3 Nh5
16. d5 Nhf4 17. Bf1 Rf8 18. Qc1 f5 {Black builds his typical kingside play.})
6... Qxf6 7. Nf3 d6 {This move order is more precise.} ({After} 7... O-O 8. e4
d6 {White has the additional possibility of playing} 9. e5) 8. e3 (8. e4 e5)
8... e5 ({It's also possible to start with} 8... c5) 9. Be2 c5 $1 10. d5 Nd7
11. e4 Nf8 ({There is nothing wrong with the alternative move order -} 11...
O-O 12. O-O Re8 13. Qc2 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8g6,Gg6f4]} 14. Rab1 Ng6 15. Rfd1 Rf8 {
[%cal Gg6f4,Gf6e7,Gf7f5] Once again, Black achieves a dream position. Later on,
he can follow with ...Nf4, ...Qe7, and ...f7-f5.}) 12. O-O ({Nothing changes} 
12. Qa4+ Bd7 13. Qb3 Rb8 {[%cal Gf8g6,Ge8g8,Gg6f4,Gf6e7,Gf7f5]}) 12... Ng6 13.
Nd2 O-O 14. f3 Qg5 ({Playing in a King's Indian style by means of} 14... Qd8
15. Qc2 f5 16. Rf2 f4 {is a decent option as well.}) 15. Kh1 f5 16. exf5 {
Preventing ...f5-f4.} ({The following line shows White might happen if White
allows ...f5-f4. Basically, Black enjoys a fantastic version of the King's
Indian Defence.} 16. Qc2 f4 17. Rab1 Qf6 18. a4 Nh8 19. a5 g5 20. a6 b6 21. Ra1
Ng6 22. Bd3 h5 23. Rfe1 g4 24. Bf1 Rf7 25. Nb3 Rg7 {Black's attack is very
dangerous.}) 16... Bxf5 17. Ne4 Bxe4 $1 {An important moment. In the arising
structure, the fight Queen+Knight vs Queen + Light-Squared bishop is always in
Black's favour. Black manages to develop a dangerous initiative on the dark
squares.} 18. fxe4 Rxf1+ (18... Rf4 $5 19. Rxf4 exf4 20. Qc2 Ne5 {[%csl Ge5]})
19. Qxf1 (19. Bxf1 Rf8) 19... Rf8 20. Qd1 (20. Qg1 Qd2) 20... Rf2 21. Bf1 Nh4
22. Qa4 (22. g3 Nf3 23. Bg2 Qh5 24. h3 (24. h4 Qg4 25. Qd3 (25. Bxf3 Qh3+ 26.
